Web Scraping: a tutorial in R

Ana I. Bento

1/13/2017

Web Scraping is a data mining technique to extract large amounts of data from websites. Also termed Screen Scraping, Web Data Extraction, Web Harvesting

The rvest package in R

  1. rvest is a package (https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rvest/rvest.pdf) that makes it easy to scrape (or harvest) data from html web pages
  1. designed to work with magrittr and xml2 so that you can express complex operations as elegant pipelines composed of simple, easily understood pieces
  1. depending on the complexity of the tasks we will need additional packages
#Install the package
#install.packages("rvest")
#Load the package
library(rvest)
## Loading required package: xml2

Checking if a website you want to harvest from is working

url=("https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=2NcJRZwAAAAJ&hl=en")
browseURL(url)

Commands read_html(): Read in the webpage

page <- read_html("https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=2NcJRZwAAAAJ&hl=en")

Commands html_nodes() and html_text(): Specify the css selector in html_nodes() and extract the text with html_text()

Get the citations on the first 20 papers on the page

citations <- page %>% html_nodes ("#gsc_a_b .gsc_a_c") %>% html_text()%>%as.numeric()
## Warning in function_list[[k]](value): NAs introduced by coercion
#Change the string to numeric using as.numeric()

Plot the data

barplot(citations, main="How many times has each paper been cited?", ylab='Number of citations', col="skyblue", xlab="")

List the co-authors

NOTE: selectorgadget for advanced css selecting: http://127.0.0.1:22088/library/rvest/doc/selectorgadget.html

Coauthors = page%>% html_nodes(css=".gsc_rsb_aa") %>% html_text()
Coauthors = as.data.frame(Coauthors)
names(Coauthors)='Coauthors'

We split off the scores from the winner and loser columns. The function str_extract from the stringr package finds a substring matching a pattern. In this case, the pattern is a sequence of 1 or more digits at the end of a line.

pattern <- " \\d+$"
sb$winnerScore <- as.numeric(str_extract(sb$winner, pattern))
sb$loserScore <- as.numeric(str_extract(sb$loser, pattern))
sb$winner <- gsub(pattern, "", sb$winner)
sb$loser <- gsub(pattern, "", sb$loser)
head(sb)
##   number       date                          site        winner

R package tabulizer for extracting data for PDF documents

The extract_tables command

Accesses the any pdf file and extract all the tables

#install.packages("ghit")
library(ghit)
#ghit::install_github(c("ropenscilabs/tabulizerjars", "ropenscilabs/tabulizer"))
library(tabulizer)
library(dplyr)
# Source the pdf file
location <- 'http://www.edd.ca.gov/jobs_and_training/warn/WARN-Report-for-7-1-2016-to-10-25-2016.pdf'
# Extract the table
out <- extract_tables(location)

We want to combine these into a single data matrix containing all of the data. We can do so most elegantly by combining do.call and rbind, passing it our list of matrices. Notice that I am excluding the last page here. The final page is the totals and summary information.

final <- do.call(rbind, out[-length(out)])

The first three rows of the matrix now contain the headers, which have not been formatted well since they take up multiple rows of the pdf table.

Lets fix that. Here I turn the matrix into a data.frame dropping the first three rows. Then I create a character vector containing the formatted headers and use that as the column names.

# table headers get extracted as rows with bad formatting. Dump them.
final <- as.data.frame(final[3:nrow(final), ])

# Column names
headers <- c('Notice.Date', 'Effective.Date', 'Received.Date', 'Company', 'City', 
             'No.of.Employees', 'Layoff/Closure')

# Apply custom column names
names(final) <- headers
head(final)

In order to manipulate the data properly , we will probably want to change the date column to a Date object as well as convert the No.of.Employees column to numeric. Here I do so using the R package dplyr.

# These dplyr steps are not strictly necessary for dumping to csv, but useful if further data 
# manipulation in R is required. 
final <- final %>%
    # Convert date columns to date objects
    mutate_each(funs(as.Date(., format='%m/%d/%Y')), Notice.Date, Effective.Date, Received.Date) %>%
    # Convert No.of.Employees to numeric
    mutate(No.of.Employees = as.numeric(levels(No.of.Employees)[No.of.Employees]))

# Write final table to disk
write.csv(final, file='CA_WARN.csv', row.names=FALSE)

We can also specify specific pages and areas

ab<-extract_tables('https://www.fia.com/sites/default/files/best_sector_times_17.pdf')
ab1<-extract_tables("http://www.fia.com/sites/default/files/external_archive/node4086/Race%20Lap%20Analysis.pdf", pages=8, guess=F, area=list(c(178, 10, 230, 500))) 
write.csv(ab, 'abtable.csv', row.names=F)

If guess = T tabulizer figures out the locations of the tables on its own Using a combination of guess to find the dominant table, and specified areas, we can extract the data we need from the PDF and combine it to provide a structured and clearly labeled dataframe.
